## BRAVEN LORETHSON, 24 — "The Burned Knight"

**PHYSICAL — Before the Burning**

The classical knight. Sandy blond hair with a copper-ginger warmth that catches firelight and goes almost red in the right sunset — shoulder-length, usually tied back loosely when he's working, falling free when he's off duty. Fair complexion, the kind that freckles across the nose and shoulders in summer and fades to cream in winter. Blue eyes — not icy blue, not pale blue, but a warm, lake-water blue. Clear and startlingly direct. The kind of eyes that make people trust him before he opens his mouth.

The Leonardo DiCaprio in *Romeo and Juliet* comparison is exactly right — that quality of being almost unfairly beautiful in a way that reads as innocent rather than vain. High cheekbones, a strong jaw that hasn't quite lost its youthful softness, a mouth that falls naturally into a half-smile. He looks younger than twenty-four. He looks like the kind of man who should be in a ballad, which is the cruelest thing about what's coming.

Tall — properly tall, a head above most men in a room. Long-limbed, lean-muscled, built for the sword rather than the wrestling ring. He moves like someone who was trained from childhood — not the rigid posture of military drill but the fluid economy of a man whose body knows where it is in space at all times. Quick hands. Light on his feet. He fights with a style that prioritizes speed and precision over brute force.

His armor at Millhaven is the Ayanite order's standard — practical, undecorated, well-maintained. He keeps it in better condition than most knights keep their dress plate. His sword is ordinary. He doesn't name it. He doesn't name his horse either. He's not that kind of knight — not the romantic who gives everything a title. He's the workman who sharpens his tools and does the job.

**PHYSICAL — After the First Burning (Millhaven)**

The left side of his face takes the worst of it — a swath of burn scarring from the jaw up past the cheekbone, pulling the skin tight, distorting the line of his mouth on that side. The ear is partly melted, the hair gone above the ear in a patch that won't grow back. His left hand is damaged — the fingers still work but the skin is mottled, waxy, and the grip is weaker than it was. He can still fight. It costs him.

The contrast is the point. The right side of his face is still beautiful — the cheekbone, the blue eye, the copper hair. The left side is ruin. In profile, from the right, he's the man he was. From the left, he's something else. He learns to stand so that people see the right side first. It's not vanity — it's tactical. The beautiful face puts people at ease. The burned face reminds them what he's capable of surviving.

**PHYSICAL — After the Second Burning (The Horns)**

Worse. Much worse. The burns extend down the left side of his neck and across the shoulder and upper arm. The scarring on his face deepens and tightens further. The left eye survives but the eyelid is damaged — it doesn't close fully, giving him a permanent half-squint that makes him look like he's always evaluating you. Which, by this point, he is.

His hair is shorter now — he cut it after the second burning because the uneven patches where it wouldn't grow made him look ragged. He keeps it cropped close on the burned side and slightly longer on the intact side, a practical asymmetry that becomes his signature. The ginger-blond has darkened slightly, as if the fire took some of the light out of it.

He wraps the worst of the hand and arm scarring in linen bandages treated with a Xarian healing salve Kaio's people provided. The salve smells of resin and something bitter. He rewraps it twice daily with the mechanical care of a man performing maintenance on a weapon.

**PSYCHOLOGY — Before Millhaven**

Genuine. That's the word for Braven before the fire. He's a genuinely good man — not naive, not simple, but good in the way that costs something. He chose the Ayanite order because he believed in service. Not in the abstract sense of theological commitment but in the practical sense of wanting to stand between vulnerable people and the things that hurt them. The lodge at Millhaven was supposed to be boring. He didn't mind boring. He liked the rhythm — patrol, maintain, report, repeat. He liked knowing every face in the village. He liked that the miller's daughter had flour in her hair and laughed at things that weren't actually funny because she was nervous around him.

He is not sophisticated. His intelligence is practical, not strategic — he reads terrain, not people. He trusts too easily. He takes oaths seriously to a degree that more worldly people would find quaint. He believes that institutions, however flawed, are better than the alternative. This belief will be tested to destruction.

Sela is not a grand passion. That's important. She's not the great love of legend. She's the woman who happens to be here, in this village, in this life, and with whom he's building something small and real through accumulated daily contact. He brings her firewood she didn't ask for. She leaves bread at the lodge wrapped in cloth. They haven't slept together. They might not for months. The relationship is in the stage of orbit — circling closer, neither one quite willing to close the distance, both knowing it's going to happen. It's the most ordinary love story in the world. That ordinariness is what makes its destruction unbearable.

**PSYCHOLOGY — After Millhaven**

Grief rearranges him. Not all at once — grief doesn't work that way, and Braven's arc depends on the reader seeing the transformation as a process rather than a switch. Initially, it's just shock. The burns, the loss, the information that Sela was taken rather than killed — all of it arrives in his nervous system before his mind can process it. He moves on autopilot through the recovery. He tells Ser Aldric Carn what happened because duty requires it. Carn's refusal to act breaks something Braven doesn't hear breaking at the time.

The grief converts to purpose when Kaio gives it a container. The Flaming Heart is Braven's grief weaponized, and he knows this on some level, and he doesn't care. Or rather — he cares, but caring about being manipulated is a luxury for people who still have something to lose. Braven has one thing left: the knowledge that Sela is alive somewhere, in Nionian hands. Everything else — honor, institutional loyalty, caution, mercy — is negotiable against that single fact.

The PTSD is real and should be written real. It's not cinematic flashbacks with wavy edges. It's the smell of woodsmoke making his hands shake. It's the way he can't sleep near a hearth. It's the moment in the Horns when the inn is burning and he *swears* he sees her at the window and rides in, and the reader doesn't know if she was there or if his damaged mind put her there, and neither does Braven, and it doesn't matter because he rode in either way.

By the end of Book One, Braven on that ship to Nionia is not the man who lived at Millhaven. The warmth is gone — not dead, but buried so deep under scar tissue (literal and psychological) that even he can't access it. The blue eyes that used to make people trust him now make people uncomfortable. Something behind them has changed. He let the last Nionian soldier go, and it's framed as the final act of the old Braven — the last mercy he'll ever give. What boards that ship is something colder. Something patient. Something that learned, from Kaio, that a man can be converted into an instrument.

**VOICE — How He Talks**

Before Millhaven: warm, direct, slightly rough-edged. He's not eloquent. He says what he means without ornamentation. Short sentences. Honest questions. He laughs easily and his laugh is unguarded.

After Millhaven: fewer words. Longer pauses. When he does speak, it's with a flatness that used to be directness but has lost its warmth. He stops asking questions he doesn't need the answer to. He stops laughing. He develops a habit of repeating the last thing someone said back to them, very quietly, as if testing whether the words mean what the speaker thinks they mean. It's unnerving.

**HABITS & TELLS**

Before: whittles wood when sitting idle — not artistic, just nervous energy finding an outlet. Sings under his breath while patrolling, old ballads, badly. Sleeps deeply and wakes slowly. Eats with appetite and without manners. Touches people casually — a hand on a shoulder, a friendly shove.

After: the whittling stops (left hand). The singing stops. Sleeps lightly if at all. Eats mechanically. Stops touching people. Develops a habit of standing with his burned side toward walls — protective positioning that becomes unconscious. Carries the Nionian insignia from Millhaven in his pocket and handles it the way someone else might handle prayer beads.

