## JOUS LORETHIAN, 24 — "The God King"

**PHYSICAL**

Strikingly, disturbingly beautiful. Not handsome — beautiful. High cheekbones sharp enough to cast shadows. Pale grey eyes that look almost silver in certain light — they have a clarity that feels unnatural, as if they're seeing slightly more of the electromagnetic spectrum than normal human eyes. Black hair worn long and unbound, falling past his shoulders in the style the Pure Way has made fashionable across Nionia. The hair is so dark it almost has a blue sheen. His skin is the Nionian pale — not unhealthy but alabaster, the complexion of an island people who've been quarrying white marble for a thousand years and have started to resemble it.

Tall, lean, architecturally precise in his proportions. He moves with a control that borders on uncanny — never a wasted gesture, never an awkward angle. It's not grace exactly. Grace implies ease. Jous moves like a man who is aware of being watched at all times and has made the performance seamless. His posture is immaculate. He stands with his chin slightly elevated — not arrogantly, but in the way of someone who is genuinely looking past you, at something in the distance only he can see.

The Warhammer God-Emperor parallel is strong and intentional — there's that same quality of a human being who has been scaled up beyond human parameters while remaining technically human. The physical beauty isn't warmth. It's *authority*. People in his presence feel an almost gravitational pull — their posture straightens, their voices quiet, their conviction sharpens. This is partially his echo-density producing a localized resonance effect that amplifies belief and certainty in nearby humans. He doesn't know this is a mechanism. He thinks it's proof.

The Jared Leto cult comparison is the other axis — the charismatic leader who has built an identity so total, so all-encompassing, that the line between genuine belief and performed divinity has ceased to exist. Jous doesn't perform being God. He *is* God, in his own experience. The performance and the reality have fused. There is no backstage Jous who takes off the mask and laughs about it. The mask is the face. The face is the mask. This is what makes him terrifying.

He dresses in white. Always. White robes of Nionian marble-weight linen, draped in the classical style — somewhere between Roman toga and religious vestment. Gold accents at the hems, at the clasp, at the wrists. A thin gold circlet — not a crown, the Pure Way rejects crowns as secular vanity — resting just above his brow. His feet are bare in the Dome Palace and sandaled in public. The bare feet are a theological statement: the God-King walks on holy ground wherever he stands. The ground becomes holy because he stands on it.

Underneath the robes, his body tells a different story. Dark circles under the eyes that the marble pallor almost hides. He's thinner than he should be — the insomnia and the visions are eroding him physically. His hands have a faint tremor that he controls through conscious effort but that surfaces when he's exhausted. He bites the inside of his cheek when he's processing a vision — there are scars in there that no one sees.

**PSYCHOLOGY**

Jous is the most dangerous kind of antagonist: one who is not wrong about everything. His echo-density is real. His visions show him real places he's never visited. His resonance effect on people in his presence is a measurable phenomenon, not mass hysteria. The Pure Way's theology is built on a genuine misinterpretation of genuine phenomena. Jous is not a fraud — he is a man who has been given evidence of his own divinity by a universe that doesn't care what he does with it.

The certainty is his cage. He has never doubted himself. Not once. Not in the convent, not during the civil war, not sitting on the throne of a conquered island with a fleet being built to his specifications. This sounds like strength and it functions as strength, but it is the most complete prison a human mind can build for itself. A man who doubts can change. A man who cannot doubt can only escalate. When reality contradicts Jous's certainty, he doesn't adjust — he reshapes reality. The Heartlands aren't cooperating? The agents are insufficiently devoted. The assassination attempt? Proof that the church is corrupt and must be purged. The hand on dark wet sand that his visions keep showing him? He won't look at it directly. It doesn't fit the narrative. He reshapes everything — everything — except that hand. And the hand keeps coming back.

The visions are getting worse since the Eldra-Veil breach, though he doesn't know that's the cause. He's seeing mainland landscapes he's never visited. Rivers he can't name. Faces. The visions used to come only during sleep paralysis — that horrible liminal state between sleep and waking where he can't move and the images pour in. Now they're bleeding into his waking hours. A flash of wet sand during a council meeting. A face he doesn't recognize superimposed over his admiral's face for a half-second. He attributes this to his divinity strengthening. He may be right. The universe is cruel in its ambiguities.

The sleep paralysis is the crack in the marble. This is where Jous is human — pinned to his bed, unable to move, flooded with images he didn't choose, terrified in a way that he cannot admit to anyone including himself. A god does not feel terror. Therefore what he feels is not terror. It is revelation. The distinction is everything and it is nothing.

His relationship with Envoy Maret — the blind Sister of the Veil — is the other crack. She has a hold on him that neither of them has found language for. She was in the convent. She knew him as a child. She is the only living person who remembers him before the certainty calcified, and her presence introduces a frequency into his echo-field that disrupts the resonance — not enough to shake him, but enough to make him *aware* that he is being shaken. He avoids being alone with her. He cannot stop himself from seeking her out.

**VOICE — How He Talks**

Prophetic register as default. He speaks in certainties — "this will be done" not "this should be done." "The future I have seen" not "I believe." He uses the royal we inconsistently — sometimes as genuine plural (he and God, who are the same person) and sometimes as singular. The inconsistency is telling. He rarely asks questions. When he does, they're rhetorical — not seeking information but testing devotion. "You do not doubt?" is not a question. It's a measurement.

When the mask slips — during a vision, near Maret, in the depths of sleep deprivation — his voice changes. Drops. Gets younger. Almost uncertain. These moments last seconds. Nobody in his inner circle acknowledges them.

He never raises his voice. He never needs to. The resonance does the work.

