## BOH VAAKOR, 19 — "The Scholar"

**PHYSICAL**

Lean and slightly underfed — the body of a teenager who forgets to eat because he found something interesting in a book three hours ago. Average height but carries himself shorter — shoulders slightly hunched, perpetual forward lean, the posture of someone who spends most of their waking hours bent over a desk or peering at something at close range. He should probably wear corrective lenses if the world had them. He squints.

*[Proposal for appearance: dark hair, messy, the kind of hair that looks like he cut it himself with a knife and then immediately forgot about it. Brown skin — let's put his origins somewhere warm. Maybe Red Coast background, or mixed parentage, something that makes him visually distinct from the pale Nionian and Heartlander-dominated Isle population without being A Statement About It — just a kid from somewhere else. Dark brown eyes that go almost black in the library's dim light. A narrow face that will fill out in his twenties but currently reads as slightly foxish. No beard — he can't grow one yet and the patchy attempts are mercifully behind him.]*

He dresses in the novice's standard-issue robes, which hang off him because they were sized for someone broader. He's rolled the sleeves up so many times they've developed a permanent crease. His hands are permanently stained with ink — not just the fingertips but deep into the nail beds, along the side of the palm where it drags across wet pages. He smells like old paper and the particular metallic tang of the Isle's archival ink. His shoes are wrong — too big, borrowed, stuffed with paper at the toes. This is not poverty. This is a person who does not think about shoes.

He carries twelve sheets of paper folded into a square in his inner pocket, covered in a notation system nobody else can read. He touches the pocket compulsively, the way someone else might check for a wallet.

**PSYCHOLOGY**

The comedic, slightly awkward, brilliant-stoner archetype is the surface — and it's a *surface*, which is what makes Boh more interesting than that archetype usually is. He genuinely is funny. He genuinely is awkward. He genuinely loses track of conversations because something someone said triggered a connection to something he read six months ago and he's now four layers deep in his own associative chain while his mouth is still producing the sounds from the previous topic. But the degree to which this reads as harmless bumbling is *cultivated*.

Not maliciously. Not even consciously, not at first. Boh figured out early — maybe age twelve, maybe younger — that being the odd, smart kid who nobody takes seriously is the most powerful position in any room. You hear everything. People talk in front of you because you register as furniture. Senior scholars leave their notes out because the weird first-circle novice obviously doesn't understand them. The mess hall gossipers include you in the conversation because you're entertaining and you never repeat anything and also you were sort of just *there* somehow. He has become the Isle's most invisible person through the paradoxical method of being the Isle's most visible oddball.

The intelligence underneath the performance is formidable. Not in the same register as Kaio — Kaio's intelligence is strategic, a chess player's gift. Boh's intelligence is *connective*. He sees patterns across systems that have no business being related. A Xarian inscription and a Roslandic folk tale and a Nionian naval record — three documents from three civilizations, filed in three different sections of the library — and Boh is the only person on the continent who has read all three and felt the thread that runs between them. His mind works like a loom. He doesn't analyze. He *weaves*.

The "playing dumb" aspect has a specific quality that separates it from manipulation. Boh isn't deceiving people for gain. He's managing how much of his actual processing they're exposed to, because the full output would be overwhelming and also because nobody asked him. He's a first-circle novice. Nobody cares what patterns he sees in the comparative mythology collection. If he walked up to a senior Elder and said "I think I've found evidence of a pan-continental echo phenomenon referenced in at least four unrelated cultural traditions and I have twelve sheets of proof in a cipher only I can read," the Elder would pat him on the head and tell him to finish his cataloguing. So he doesn't say it. He writes it in notation nobody can read and he keeps cataloguing and he *waits for the right person to show it to*.

Finding Corvath — the right person — is the turning point. Boh doesn't go through proper channels because proper channels would bury it. He finds a non-standard way to reach the one scholar whose work suggests he'd understand. When Corvath summons him within days, Boh understands for the first time that the thing he found is real, and dangerous, and that his life is about to change in ways the playing-dumb strategy can't navigate.

The stoner quality: *[Proposal: Boh doesn't actually smoke anything (though he would if he could). The "stoner" vibe comes from his natural cognitive rhythm — he's distractible, tangential, occasionally says things that sound like non sequiturs but are actually six inferential steps ahead of the conversation. He spaces out mid-sentence. He laughs at things nobody else finds funny because the humor is in the pattern-match, not the content. He's the kid who's always slightly somewhere else. The Isle's other novices think he's a harmless weirdo. The one or two who've glimpsed what he's actually doing have revised that assessment.]*.

**VOICE — How He Talks**

Fast, tangential, peppered with references that his listener doesn't catch. He starts sentences in the middle of thoughts. He says "wait, no, actually—" a lot. He asks questions that seem random and are in fact precisely targeted, but the targeting is invisible because the delivery is so scattered. He mumbles when he's thinking and speaks clearly when he's performing being weird. He has a habit of trailing off when he realizes the person he's talking to can't follow where he's going, and then pivoting to something mundane with a slightly deflated "anyway."

When he's genuinely excited about a connection — the fire-song, the Xarian inscription match — the scattered quality drops completely. His speech becomes focused, rapid, precise. Anyone who witnessed this shift would immediately revise their opinion of him. Almost nobody witnesses it.

**HABITS & TELLS**

Chews the end of his writing stylus. Hums while walking — not songs, just tones, sometimes the intervals between notes in the fire-song he's studying. Reads while eating and has stained more than one library book with porridge. Sleeps in the archive when a research thread has him — curled up on the floor between shelves, his folded notes under his head like a pillow. Categorizes people by which section of the library they'd be filed in. Cannot remember what day it is. Always knows exactly what page he was on in any book he's reading.

