KAIO ARGENHOLD — Additions
Personal items: A Xarian smoking pipe — carved hardwood, dark with use, compact enough to fit in a coat pocket. He brought a finite supply of k'utz leaf from the peninsula and knows he'll run out. A woven bracelet on his left wrist — Xarian thread-work in red and black with a small blue glass bead at the clasp, a nazar-equivalent meant to ward against envy and ill intent. He never removes it. It's the one piece of Xaria he wears openly, and people notice it without understanding it. The bracelet was given to him by someone significant in Xaria — who exactly remains a Book One mystery.

BRAVEN LORETHSON — Additions
Personal item: The Nionian insignia taken from the soldier at Millhaven. Not worn — carried in his pocket, handled like prayer beads. After the second burning, it becomes the only object he touches compulsively. It's his compass. It points toward Nionia.

BOH VAAKOR — Background Revision
Sangrean origins. Mixed parentage — a Sangrean mother from the Selvaverde province (Botano vassal territory, jungle country, warm-blooded and colorful) and a father who was either Heartlander or unknown. This gives him olive-brown skin, dark curly hair he cuts badly, and a faint Sangrean lilt under his Munnish that surfaces when he's excited or tired. It also connects him to the Isle's more subversive circles — the Sangrean scholarly tradition is wilder, less orthodox, more comfortable with heresy and unconventional thinking. The students who stay up too late in the wrong sections, the ones debating Logosian theory and passing around banned Cogitant Letters — Boh drifts naturally into their orbit. Not as a leader. As the quiet one in the corner who hears everything and occasionally says something that makes everyone else go silent for a second.
Personal item: The twelve folded sheets in his pocket, covered in his private notation. Also — a small carved wooden bird his mother sent him when he was accepted to the Isle. Sangrean work, bright paint mostly worn off. He keeps it on his desk next to whatever he's reading. It doesn't mean anything symbolic. It just means his mother.

ANGYA GREENHAND — Scar Revision
The scar between thumb and forefinger on her right hand — from her mother's loom, age seven. Her mother Dalla died when Angya was fourteen, a lung disease from years of breathing textile dust in poorly ventilated guild halls. The scar is the last physical thing that connects Angya to her. She flexes it when angry, opens and closes the hand. Sometimes she catches herself doing it during council sessions and stops, because it feels too private for that room.
Personal item: A weaver's shuttle — her mother's, small enough to fit in a pocket. Wooden, smooth from decades of use. She doesn't carry it publicly. It lives in her quarters, on the nightstand. She holds it when she can't sleep.

VALO IRONSIDE — Style Revision
Valo is the best-dressed person in any room he enters, and the effort is invisible. His blacks are different blacks — raven-black wool, charcoal-black leather, ink-black silk at the collar. The tailoring is impeccable, close-cut, architectural. He sources fabric through channels nobody else in Rosland uses — Sangrean cotton, Heartlander silver-thread, even Nionian linen when he can get it. In a culture of practical, rough-hewn Roslandic fashion, he dresses like a blade someone lacquered. It reads as aristocratic vanity to people who don't look closely. People who look closely notice that the clothes are armor — every seam designed to make him look untouchable, composed, finished. He is a trendsetter without trying to be. Young nobles in Fairhaven have started wearing higher collars.
Personal item: A black iron ring on his right hand — unadorned, undecorated, the only piece of jewelry he wears. He has never taken it off. Whether this is loyalty, habit, or evidence is one of the questions the reader carries.

VENANIA SARKO — Addition
Personal item: Her grandmother's hunting knife — bone handle, short blade, resharpened so many times the steel has narrowed to a sliver. She was buried with the sheath but Venania kept the knife. It's the tool she uses for everything — cutting rope, cleaning game, marking trail. It'll be the knife she's holding when she looks down at the beach and sees the shape.

That's the full set. Clean, tight, everything anchored. Ready to build Millhaven when you are.




